  "answer": "**Andreas (cynewulf-andreas-07b573, chapter 1):** The foundational moment of God's intervention comes in two moves. First, Matthew cries out from his Mermedonian prison and God answers directly: 'Hold fast, my Matthew! Do not lose heart. I shall not leave you lost in this torment, nor forsake My own. I shall free you from bondage... I will send Andrew to save you from sorrow' (p-bdbda7). Second, God commands Andrew on the shoreline and then disguises himself as a ship captain — 'They were the Lord Himself, the Almighty King, with his angels two, disguised in the likeness of lonely shipmen' (p-24dbdc) — ferrying Andrew toward Mermedonia while concealing his identity.\n\n**Manusmrti, Book 1 (unknown-manusmrti-347b76, chapter 1):** The foundational moment is the cosmogony narrated in verses Mn_1.5–1.26. The universe begins in formless darkness: 'This universe existed as darkness, unperceived, without distinctive marks, unknowable, as if wholly asleep on all sides' (p-61df11). The Self-existent One (Svayambhū) then manifests himself, creates the waters through contemplation, and casts his seed into them (p-54fad8). The seed becomes a golden egg from which Brahmā is born (p-153021). He then splits the egg to form heaven and earth (p-cd6713, p-3bd729), generates mind, ego, and the five sense elements from himself (p-f689c4), assigns names and actions to all beings (p-3a6c83), and separates Dharma from non-Dharma (p-84ef7f).\n\n**What each text needs its god to be capable of:**\n\nAndreas needs a God of *personal intervention and historical presence*. He must be able to hear individual prayer and respond in real time, issue commands to specific followers, disguise himself in human form, and orchestrate rescue across geography and time. His power is relational and narrative — it operates through conversation, disguise, and commission. The poem's theology demands a God who is *in* history, managing it from within, responding to the faithful rather than simply setting the cosmos running.\n\nManusmrti needs a God of *ontological self-sufficiency and cosmogonic generativity*. Brahmā is not summoned by prayer; he self-originates from within formless matter, creates through contemplation (not command to another), and generates the very categories of existence — space, time, dharma, the Vedas, species names and distinct duties. His power is structural: he produces the framework within which all subsequent existence is intelligible. The text demands a God who is complete unto himself, who creates not just beings but the distinctions and norms by which beings are organized.\n\nIn short: Andreas needs a god who responds; Manusmrti needs a god who generates. One theology is built on rescue within a fallen situation; the other is built on the self-producing ground of all situation.",
